class Solution {
    public int numberOfPairs(int[][] points) {
        int pairs = 0;
        Arrays.sort(points, (a, b) -> {
            if (a[0] != b[0]) {
                return a[0] - b[0];
            } else {
                return b[1] - a[1];
            }
        });
        int n = points.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                if (isGood(points, i, j)) {
                    pairs++;
                }
            }
        }
        return pairs;
    }

    public boolean isGood(int[][] points, int index1, int index2) {
        int n = points.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (i == index1 || i == index2) {
                continue;
            }
            if (points[i][0] >= points[index1][0] && points[i][0] <= points[index2][0] && points[i][1] >= points[index2][1] && points[i][1] <= points[index1][1]) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

This code sorts the points array in ascending order of their x-coordinates, and then in descending order of their y-coordinates. It then iterates over the sorted array and for each pair of points, checks if the pair is good. A pair of points is good if there are no other points in the rectangle they make. The isGood method checks this by iterating over all points and checking if any point is inside the rectangle made by the two points. If it finds such a point, it returns false; otherwise, it returns true.

