The dfs method is a depth-first search algorithm used to count the number of nodes reachable from a given node. The count starts from 1 for the current node, and it is incremented by the count of nodes reachable from the next nodes. If a next node is not visited, the dfs method is called recursively.

The time complexity of the solution is O(n^2) where n is the number of teams. This is because in the worst case, each team is connected to all other teams, and dfs is called for each team. The space complexity is O(n^2) because the graph is stored as an adjacency list.

